Quality of Red Wine by Christoph Knoop

Abstract

What makes a good wine? Centuries of tradition, solid craftsmanship? Im sure it is. But the quality of a wine also has something to do with what it contains chemically.The Question: Can we derive its quality from the chemical composition of a wine?

Source of Dataset

P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

Available at: [@Elsevier] http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.dss.2009.05.016 [Pre-press (pdf)] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/winequality09.pdf [bib] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/dss09.bib

Analysis

In this document I examine the quality of red wines. For this I use a data set of four authors (more information at Source of Dataset) provided by Udacity. It contains data on 1599 wines. Listed are 13 variables. 11 of them are concerned with the chemical composition of the wines, one with the result of qualitative wine tests. The 13th variable is the ID of the wine. The Dataset includes samples of the Portugese Vinho Verde wine.

Explanation of the attributes

This explanation is part of the original dataset: 1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines

4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine

6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

10 - sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine

Output variable (based on sensory data): 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

The degree of sweetness of the wine depends on the residual sugar. Here it makes sense to create a new variable that divides the wines into four categories. These categories are derived from European Union regulation. According to this, a wine with up to 4 mg sugar per litre is considered dry, between 5 and 12 mg per litre as semi-dry, between 13 and 45 grams per litre as medium and with a sugar value of more than 45 grams per litre as sweet.We call that new variable sweetness.

Here is the source: *https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweetness_of_wine*

In order to increase the significance of our sugar histograms, the second plot is a zoom into the range up to a sugar content of 6 grams per litre. In the third diagram I scaled the X-axis with Log10() to show the distribution even more clearly.

The plots show Most of the wines can be classified in the dry category, between 1.9 (1st quartile) and 2.6 (3rd quartile). However, we have an outlier with a significantly higher sugar content of up to 15.5.

Our variable sweetness shows that the majority of the wines examined have the attribute dry according to the EU classification.

Most of the wines have a sodium chloride content between 0.07 grams per liter (1st quartile) and 0.09 grams per liter (3rd quartile). The median is 0.079 grams per liter, the average is 0.08747 grams per liter. Occasionally we find outliers of up to 0.611 grams per litre in the wines.

The salt content is responsible for the occurrence of tartar. Whether this has an effect on the evaluation of wine testers will be analysed at a later date.

Sulphur is important for the preservation of a wine, otherwise the liquids can oxidize very quickly. Moreover, sulphur enhances the taste, without sulphur a wine would taste more like a path. Above all sweet wines have to be sulphured. There are discussions whether sulphurization has a negative effect on the quality of the wine. We can investigate this later. therefore the question: Does low sulphur ensure more quality?

This free sulphur is what can possibly smell and cause health problems if the wine has been over-sulphured. For the health evaluation it depends therefore on the content of free sulphurous acid. Free sulphur above 50 mg/litre is clearly noticeable.

In relation to the total sulphur, the free sulphurous acid accounts for almost 20 percent and the bound sulphur for more than 80 percent.

In our data set, the low value for free sulfur is 1.0, the highest value is 72 (median 14, average 15.87).

The lowest value for total sulphur is 6, the highest is 289, the median is 38, the average is 46.47.

For both values we see a large gap between the 3rd quartile and the highest value. So we are dealing here with extreme outliers.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9901  0.9956  0.9968  0.9967  0.9978  1.0037

The density of the wine indicates something for the proportion of must in the liquid. The higher, the heavier the must, for example late ripened grapes with a high sugar content. However, the sugar content of the must is only part of the taste of a wine.

As a rule of thumb, the sweeter a wine, the higher its density.

The lowest density in our data set is 0.9901, the highest 1.0037. The median is 0.9968, the average is 0.9968. Since the maximum value of 1.0037 is only slightly higher than the 3rd quantile, we obviously only have to deal with a few and not particularly extreme outliers.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.740   3.210   3.310   3.311   3.400   4.010

The pH value plays an important role in the taste of wine and is connected to the acids contained in the wine. In our data set most of the wines examined show a value from 3,210 (1st quartile) to 3.4 (3rd quartile). The smallest value is 2.74, the highest is 4.01. The median is 3.310, the average is 3.311. So the median and average are almost congruent, meaning: there are hardly any outliers.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.3300  0.5500  0.6200  0.6581  0.7300  2.0000

The variable sulphates describes the potassium content of the wine. Potassium is part of the acidity of the wine. Too little potassium has a negative effect on the taste. Too much potassium, on the other hand, can lead to a too high pH value and thus to a soapy taste.

The smallest value is 0.33, the highest is 2, the median is 0.62, the average 0.6581, the 3rd quantile 0.73. This means that the maximum value of 2 is a severe outlier.

The alcohol value in wine is not necessarily a quality feature. However, alcohol has an influence on the taste. A higher alcohol content usually provides a fuller, more intense aroma. The fermentation of wines with a low alcohol content was usually stopped early, so that more residual sugar often remains in the wine. Say: The wine is usually sweeter. Often wine has an alcohol value between 9 and 11 percent. In our data set, the average alcohol content is 10.42 percent. The median is 10.20 percent. The lowest value is 8.4 percent, the highest 14.9 percent.

Univariate Analysis

In the dataset we find many variables whose values can influence the quality of a wine. However, even experts have different points of view as to which values and at what level make up a good wine. The bottom line is that it is a combination of the different ingredients that make a wine stand out.

The task of the following analysis will be to identify links between the individual characteristics of the wine and to try to reconcile specific information on ingredients with the established quality of the wine.

The quality variable is indispensable for this, its our main feature. The quality of a wine cannot be measured objectively on the basis of figures. However, the various test results with which wine experts have evaluated our data set allow us to draw conclusions and establish connections.

Bivariate Plots Section

At the beginning, we use ggcorr to provide a rough overview of the correlations between the individual variables. We are particularly interested in what the quality of the wines.

After a look at our overview it becomes clear that the quality shows with others values have hardly any stronger correlations. Only for the alcohol content (corr 0.5) and for the proportion The volatile acidity (correlation of 0.4) shows stronger correlations. Compound s still exist between quality and sulphur as well as quality and citric acid (each 0.3).
We assume that with values of +/- 0.3 significant correlations exist, with values between 0.4 and 0.6 of strong correlations can be spoken and values above +/- 0.7 are very high. strong correlations. The latter, however, come in our record not before.

With ggpairs we then look at some values with strong correlation still a little more precisely. These pairs of variables are now to be examined in more detail.

The wines of the highest quality have a high alcohol content on average. The higher the quality of the wine, the higher the average alcohol content. The exception is quality level 5, in which there are many wines with an alcohol content of less than 10 percent. The average alcohol content of this quality class is therefore slightly lower than that of grades 4 and 5, but the average alcohol content rises sharply for higher quality classes.

In principle, the wines of higher quality show less volatile acidity than the wines of the lower quality classes. This was to be expected, because acidity can give the wine a vinegar taste. The fact that some wines with a high proportion nevertheless slip into the higher quality classes could indicate that some testers certainly appreciate the high proportion of volatile acidity as a special note of the wine.

High quality wines also have an average higher value of sulphates in our data set. This can be determined with both the average and the median. This is important because there are many outliers, especially in quality levels 5 and 6, and the median tends to be less sensitive. It should also be noted that in the two highest measured quality levels (7 and 8) there are no sulphate values above 1.7, but at the lower values the Outlets go up to the value 2.

Quality and citric acid are also related. On average, the higher quality wines contain more citric acid. However, the range of values is very wide, especially in the lower quality classes. And: Even high class wines (quality 8) contain very little citric acid in individual cases.

A final quick test that confirms our observations from the correlation overview. In our data set, the sweetness of the wine has no clear influence on the quality of the wine. The average values are almost the same in the different quality levels. However, it is remarkable that the particularly sweet wines (from a sugar content of 12) can only be found as outliers in the middle quality classes.

There is a correlation between density and alcohol content. As the graph shows, wines with a higher alcohol content have a lower average density.

In our data set there is a relationship between the density of the wines and the fixed acidity. The higher the density of the wine, the higher the fixed acidity.

The alcohol content has an effect on the quality of the wine, as does the volatile acidity. However, a test to determine whether these two variables are also related is negative. Only wines with the highest measured alcohol values tend to have a lower acid content. However, the values measured there are not very numerous.

Finally, we look at the values of our variable pair with the strongest correlation - density and fixed acidity. The higher the density of the wine, the higher the fixed acidity.

Bivariate Analysis

The question of this analysis is simple to summarize: What is the quality of a good wine? In addition to the quality, four of our variables seem to be of particular importance. The alcohol content of good wines is on average higher. Furthermore, good wines have a lower volatile acidity content. The sulphur content is also higher for wines of higher quality than for wines of lower quality. However, it should be noted that the rule more sulphur, higher quality does not work. None of the particularly high-quality wines has a sulphur value above 1.2. In contrast, the wines of lower quality have values of 1.5 as outliers. The amount of citric acid also seems to have an influence on the quality of the wine. For example, the high-class wines have on average a higher proportion of citric acid. However, even this variable does not seem to be suitable for significantly determining the quality of the wine. This means that even wines of a high quality level have values close to zero.

It should be noted that values that more or less correlate with the quality of the wine are not linked to each other. It could be assumed that - if a high alcohol value is more indicative of the quality of a wine - wines with a low proportion of volatile acidity also have a high alcohol content. However, this connection is not given in our data set.

We measured the highest correlation between the density and the proportion of fixed acidity. This allows the conclusion that during the fermentation process a wine with a high must content forms the measured acids faster than with a low must content.

Multivariate Plots Section

To make the analysis more meaningful, we first arrange the wines according to quality in three bins: low quality (1-4), medium quality (5-6) and high quality (7-10). When we combine the values for alcohol, sulphates and quality, we see that the wines with high quality increasingly have both a high alcohol and a high sulphur value.

When combining volatile acidity, alcohol content and quality of wines, we find that wines of higher quality often have a higher alcohol content and a low content of volatile acidity.

As we can see, good quality wines often contain a higher proportion of citric acid and at the same time a higher proportion of sulphur. The question of whether the alcohol content also plays a decisive role here must be answered in the negative with regard to our graph. Wines with high and low alcohol content do not show a clear pattern here. For more expressiveness, I cut the Y-axis and concentrated on the area in which most of the values lie.

On the basis of this graph we can observe the interaction between the exploitation of volatile acidity, citric acidity and the quality level of the wine. Most of the good wines have a high level of citric acidity and a low level of volatile acidity.

Since the alcohol content correlates with both density and quality, we want to examine in this graph whether all three variables have patterns in common. A connection, however, is hardly evident here. The wines of high quality always have a higher alcohol content. In contrast to wines of medium quality, however, this does not seem to make much of a difference in density.

Finally, we examine whether the variables, which showed strong correlations among each other in the entire data set, behave similarly for all wine quality levels. This is the case, there are no serious differences between the individual quality levels.

Multivariate Analysis

If we connect the variables, which also individually show a correlation with the quality, we can determine clear connections. What is surprising, however, is how many variables do not seem to have a direct effect on the quality of the wine, for example its density. This picture does not change even if we examine the wines individually according to their quality classes.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot describes the ratio between sulphate and citric acid, taking into account the alcohol content and quality of the wine. This allows four different variables to be related to each other.

Clearly recognizable: The wines of the top class show rather a higher value with the sulphates, at the same time they also contain more citric acid. The wines of low quality fall behind in both categories. The alcohol content is of secondary importance.

To make the plot as attractive as possible, I cut off the Y and X axes and concentrate on the area where most of the values are located. The theme used is the economist theme (ggthemes).

Plot Two

Description Two

The second plot shows the relationship between volatile acidity and citric acidity and their effect on the quality of the wines. It should be noted that Wines of higher quality have a rather low proportion of volatile acidity and are for the most part below the average content of the wines in our data set. On the other hand, they have a higher citric acid content than rather poorer wines.

Also in this plot the X- and Y-axis were cut off, the plot concentrates on the part with especially many values. The solarize layout of the ggthemes library was used for this graphic.

Plot Three

Description Three

The third plot shows that the wines of high quality have on average higher alcohol values and at the same time higher proportions of sulphates.

Reflection

It is difficult to find clear patterns in the chemical composition when evaluating wines. For example, there are individual variables that correlate with quality, such as alcohol content or volatile acidity. The sulphates and citric acid content also show a weaker correlation with quality. However, these variables do not correlate with each other. In other words: a wine with a lot of alcohol (which indicates a high quality) does not necessarily have a particularly low content of volatile acidity, at least not to the extent that the alcohol correlates with the quality.

This means that it may be difficult to put together the perfect chemical recipe for a good wine, even if there are some basic rules such as a low content of volatile acidity. Many different factors seem to have flowed into the assessments of the testers. To a certain extent, taste is simply a question of taste - and not of chemistry.
